{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3bc4feb1-39d0-4d06-8e48-595038eebff0","content":"## What happened\n\n**C# 14 adds first-class span support with implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`.** This changes overload resolution:\n\n| Version | `array.Contains(num)` resolves to |\n|---|---|\n| C# 13 / .NET 9 | `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` ✅ |\n| C# 14 / .NET 10 | `MemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` ❌ |\n\nThe `MemoryExtensions` overload wins because `int[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is now a more specific implicit conversion than `int[]` → `IEnumerable<int>`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, the expression tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) cannot handle it and throws at runtime.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nDisambiguate back to the `Enumerable` overload. Either call it explicitly:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nOr cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` so the span conversion doesn't participate in overload resolution:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth restore the original `Enumerable.Contains` resolution and work in interpreted expression trees.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"280cff81-4b87-4e94-9a48-d1147893f13b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), which changes how extension methods are resolved.\n\nBut more specifically, I think the issue is related to how `System.Linq.Enumer